content.text:
Good call. You can do this with `background-image` using `linear-gradient` for the broken segments, and a `steps(1)` animation to swap between different break patterns for the chunky jitter:

```css
nav a:hover,
nav a:focus-visible {
  border-bottom-color: transparent;
  animation: jitter-underline 0.4s steps(1) infinite;
}

@keyframes jitter-underline {
  0%   { background-image: linear-gradient(90deg, currentColor 12%, transparent 12% 20%, currentColor 20% 55%, transparent 55% 62%, currentColor 62%); }
  25%  { background-image: linear-gradient(90deg, currentColor 18%, transparent 18% 28%, currentColor 28% 48%, transparent 48% 58%, currentColor 58% 90%, transparent 90%); }
  50%  { background-image: linear-gradient(90deg, currentColor 8%, transparent 8% 15%, currentColor 15% 42%, transparent 42% 50%, currentColor 50% 78%, transparent 78% 85%, currentColor 85%); }
  75%  { background-image: linear-gradient(90deg, currentColor 22%, transparent 22% 30%, currentColor 30% 60%, transparent 60% 68%, currentColor 68% 88%, transparent 88%); }
}
```

With `background-size: 100% 1px`, `background-repeat: no-repeat`, and `background-position: bottom` to place it where the border was.

Could also vary `background-position-y` slightly at each keyframe (like `calc(100% - 1px)` vs `100%`) for subtle vertical jitter.

Want me to implement this?

